[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(14) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "I will kindle a fire in the forest thereof.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The “forest” thus referred to may be either literally the woods, then covering a larger surface than in later times, at Kirjath-jearim (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 132:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Samuel 7:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), or the wood of the lone wilderness of Ziph (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Samuel 23:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), or the valley of Rephaim (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Samuel 5:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), or, figuratively, the royal palace, which, from its cedar columns (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Kings 7:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Kings 10:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), was known as “the house of the forest of Lebanon.” (Comp. the comparison of the king’s house to “Gilead and the head of Lebanon,” in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 22:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) The desolation wrought by an invading army such as that of Nebuchadnezzar, cutting down the “choice fir-trees of Lebanon and the forest of Carmel” (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Kings 19:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), showed itself in this destruction of forests in its most conspicuous form, and explains the comparative scarcity of trees in modern Palestine. So Assur-nasirpal narrates, in the history of his conquests, how he had cut down the pine, box, cypress, and other trees of the forest (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Records of the Past, iii.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " p. 74).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
